-- Stability Deduction Example
--
-- Demonstrates how the deduction theorem preserves stability:
-- If the body has stable credence, the lambda has stable credence.
--
-- In CredTT: Gamma, x:A |- b:B @ c  implies  Gamma |- \x.b : A -> B @ c
-- Stability: If c is Stable1, then the lambda's credence is Stable1.

-- Postulate: we have a term a of type A at credence 1 (definitely stable)
postulate a : A [ 1 ]

-- Postulate: a function that preserves full credence
postulate f : A -> B [ 1 ]

-- Derive: applying f to a gives B at credence 1*1 = 1
derive b : B [ 1 ] from a by apply f

-- Stability analysis:
-- - a has credence 1, which is Stable1 (bounded away from 0)
-- - f has credence 1, which is Stable1
-- - By app-stability: Stable1 * Stable1 = Stable1
-- - Therefore b has credence 1, which is Stable1

-- The deduction theorem (lambda abstraction) preserves this:
-- \x. f x : A -> B @ 1 is also Stable1
